{
  "_description": "PRICE-ELASTIC BASELINE + POLICY OVERLAY example (Feedback Option A composed with supply-side policy). Two scenarios share an identical tightening market (cap 480 -> 400 Mt, 3 participants, banking allowed, manual expected price 90) and the SAME price-elastic baseline: reference_carbon_price = 55 with output_price_elasticity 0.4/0.5/0.2, so carbon-intensive activity contracts when the price runs above the reference, E_base(P) = E0 * max(0, 1 - eps*(P - 55)/55), solved INSIDE market clearing (docs/feedback-price-elastic-baseline.md). 'Elastic baseline, no policy' prices 46.37 -> 68.14. 'Elastic baseline + auction floor + MSR' adds two policy layers on the same elastic market: (1) an auction reserve floor rising 56 -> 64 that binds in 2026 (price = 56.00, 35.38 Mt unsold to reserve) and (2) a bank-threshold MSR (upper threshold 20 Mt, withhold rate 12%) fed by Petrochemical's banked surplus (26.47 Mt/yr at 100% free allocation), which withholds 34.32/31.92/29.52/27.12 Mt in 2027-2030 and lifts the price OFF the floor from 2027 (61.15/65.94/70.73/75.52 vs floors 58/60/62/64). Observe how the elastic baseline dampens what the MSR withdrawal would do to an inelastic market: the demand-destruction channel adds ~3.6 Mt/(EUR/t) of effective demand slope around the reference price, so a ~30 Mt withdrawal moves the price by only ~7 EUR. Compare 'Equilibrium Carbon Price', 'Unsold Allowances', 'MSR Withheld' and 'MSR Reserve Pool' across the two scenarios.",
